"""mkt-original: Exodus 1–3
Type: original
Book: exodus
Chapters: 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-exodus-1-3-fill.py

Ch 1: The oppression of Israel in Egypt — six multiplication verbs (Gen 1:28 fulfillment),
  the decree against Hebrew males, the midwives' fear of God over Pharaoh.
  Key terms: sharatz (swarm/teem), yada (covenantal knowledge), marar (bitter),
  yirat Elohim (fear of God).
Ch 2: Moses's birth, ark-basket (teva = same word as Noah's ark), exile to Midian.
  Key terms: ki-tov (that he was good, Gen 1 echo), teva (ark), mashah (draw out),
  zakar (remember covenant), vayeda (covenantal knowing).
Ch 3: The burning bush, the divine name, the Exodus commission.
  Key terms: malach YHWH (angel of the LORD), sneh (thornbush), ehyeh (I AM/I WILL BE),
  ra'o raiti (infinitive absolute emphasis), Elohei avraham/yitzchak/yaakov.

Note: ch 3 v.14 already present in the file (the ehyeh asher ehyeh entry).
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"1": {
"1": "<p><strong>ve'eleh shemot bnei Yisrael</strong> (<em>wĕʾēlleh šĕmôt bĕnê yiśrāʾēl</em>): 'And these are the names of the sons of Israel.' The Hebrew title of the book is <em>Shemot</em> (Names), not Exodus — names signal covenantal identity, and the whole book is about the people named by YHWH. The opening <em>ve'eleh</em> (and these) links to Genesis's ending, continuing the one narrative of YHWH's covenantal family. Each name listed is a covenant heir whose descendants YHWH will redeem.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>Reuven Shimon Levi viYehudah</strong>: The listing of the twelve sons mirrors the tribal registers of Genesis 46 and Numbers 1. The genealogical record is a covenant document — listing those to whom YHWH made promises (Gen 12; 15; 17; 26; 28). Legal genealogies in the ancient Near East established inheritance rights; this genealogy establishes the covenant heirs who have a claim on YHWH's promise to the patriarchs.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>Yissachar Zevulun uVinyamin</strong>: The continuation of the tribal list through the Leah-sons and Benjamin. Each name embeds a genealogical story from Genesis — Issachar (reward, Gen 30:18), Zebulun (honor/dwell, Gen 30:20), Benjamin (son of the right hand, Gen 35:18). The compression of the patriarchal narratives into a bare list at the Exodus opening shows that the Exodus is the continuation and fulfillment of what God began with the patriarchs.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>Dan veNaftali Gad ve'Asher</strong>: The sons of Bilhah and Zilpah complete the twelve. The full tribal catalog before the oppression narrative establishes that all twelve are equally heirs of the covenant — there is no partial Israel. YHWH's redemption will not leave any tribe behind; the Exodus is for the whole covenant people, not a favored subset.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>vayhi kol-nefesh yotzei yerech-Yaakov shivim nefesh</strong> (<em>wayhî kol-nepeš yōṣĕʾê yereḵ-yaʿăqōb šibʿîm nāpeš</em>): 'All the persons who came from Jacob's loins were seventy souls.' <em>Nefesh</em> (H5315, soul/person/life-force) — each member of the covenant community is a <em>nefesh</em>, a living being bearing the image of God (Gen 2:7 — man became a living nefesh). Seventy is a significant symbolic number in the OT (seventy nations in Gen 10; seventy elders of Israel in Exod 24:1; the seventy years of exile in Jer 29:10).</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>vayamot Yosef vekhol-echav vekhol hador hahu</strong>: 'Joseph died, and all his brothers, and all that generation.' The transition from the patriarchal era to the oppression: the generation that knew Joseph and his saving role dies. The forgetting of Joseph by the new Pharaoh (v.8) is thus not merely political ingratitude but the erasure of covenantal memory. When the people who witnessed God's saving acts die without passing on the memory, the covenant community becomes vulnerable — a warning for every generation.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>vayifru vayishretzu vayirbu vayaattsemu bim'od m'od</strong> (<em>wayyipĕrû wayyišrĕṣû wayyirbû wayyaʿaṣmû bimĕʾōd mĕʾōd</em>): 'The Israelites were fruitful and swarmed and multiplied and grew exceedingly strong.' Six verbs in rapid succession — the most concentrated description of population growth in the OT. <em>Sharatz</em> (H8317, swarm/teem) is the word used in Gen 1:20 for the swarming of creatures in the sea — Israel's multiplication is deliberately compared to the original creation-flourishing. The Abrahamic promise (Gen 17:2 — I will multiply you exceedingly) is fulfilled against the odds: <em>vatimale ha'aretz otam</em> (the land was filled with them) echoes Gen 1:28 (fill the earth).</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>vayaqam melek chadash al-Mitsrayim asher lo-yada et-Yosef</strong> (<em>wayyāqom melek ḥādāš ʿal-miṣrāyim ʾăšer lōʾ-yādaʿ ʾet-yôsēp</em>): 'A new king arose over Egypt who did not know Joseph.' <em>Lo-yada</em> (did not know): <em>yada</em> (H3045) is covenantal intimacy and relational recognition, not merely factual awareness. The new Pharaoh does not merely lack information about Joseph — he refuses to recognize the covenantal reality that Joseph represented. Political amnesia as a form of covenant-blindness: deliberately not-knowing what connects the powerful to their obligations.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>vayomer el-ammo hinei am bnei Yisrael rav ve'atsum mimenu</strong>: 'He said to his people: the people of the children of Israel are too numerous and too mighty for us.' <em>Rav ve'atsum</em> (numerous and mighty): the same terms used in v.7 for Israel's growth — Pharaoh's fear response perfectly mirrors what YHWH's blessing produced. The blessing of the covenant people becomes the pretext for their oppression. This is the recurring OT pattern: the flourishing of YHWH's covenant community provokes imperial anxiety.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>hava nithachkema lo</strong> (<em>hābāh niṯḥakkĕmāh-llô</em>): 'Come, let us deal wisely/shrewdly with them.' <em>Nithachkema</em> (Hitpael of chakam, H2449, be wise): the deliberative reflexive — the council of empire deliberating cunning strategy against the covenant people. The supreme irony: Pharaoh's wisdom (chakam) is the anti-type of true wisdom (Prov 9:10: the fear of YHWH is the beginning of wisdom). The wisest nation on earth devises a plan that ultimately destroys itself, while the ones it tries to suppress multiply further (v.12).</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>vayasimu alav sarei missim</strong> (<em>wayyāśîmû ʿālāw śārê missîm</em>): 'They appointed over them forced-labor taskmasters.' <em>Missim</em> (H4522, forced labor/tribute levies) is the specific term for the corvee system of imperial labor conscription. <em>Sarei missim</em> (supervisors of forced labor) are the administrative machinery of oppression. Building <em>Pitom</em> and <em>Ra'amses</em> (store-cities) — the wealth of empire built on the bodies of covenant people. The counter-image is Paul's church-as-temple being built with living stones (1 Pet 2:5) through willing participation.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>ka'asher ye'anu oto ken yirbeh viken yifrotz</strong> (<em>kaʾăšer yĕʿannû ʾōtô kēn yirbeh wĕḵēn yiproṣ</em>): 'The more they afflicted them, the more they multiplied and spread.' <em>Anah</em> (H6031, afflict/humble/oppress) — the same root used for the affliction YHWH predicted to Abraham (Gen 15:13: your descendants will be <em>ani</em> in a land not theirs). The covenant curse of oppression paradoxically fuels the covenant blessing of multiplication. <em>Yifrotz</em> (spread, H6555) — breaking out/spreading rapidly — the same root used when Jacob's prosperity broke out (Gen 30:43) and when the Davidic covenant promises spread (2 Sam 5:20).</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>vaya'avidu Mitsrayim et-bnei Yisrael befarech</strong> (<em>wayyaʿăbidû miṣrāyim ʾet-bĕnê yiśrāʾēl bĕpāreḵ</em>): 'Egypt made the Israelites serve with crushing labor.' <em>Farech</em> (H6531, crushing labor/harshness): the specific term for the severity of forced labor — occurring only here and in Lev 25:43, 46, 53, where YHWH explicitly forbids Israelites from imposing <em>farech</em> on one another, because they know what it is like. The Exodus becomes the ethical foundation for Israel's labor laws.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>vayemareru et-chayyeihem ba'avoda kasha</strong> (<em>waymārărû ʾet-ḥayyêhem bāʿăbōdāh qāšāh</em>): 'They made their lives bitter with hard labor.' <em>Marar</em> (H4843, bitter/make bitter): the same root as the bitter waters of Marah (Exod 15:23), as Naomi's name-change to Mara (Ruth 1:20), and as the bitter herbs of the Passover (Exod 12:8). The bitterness of Egypt is ritually remembered in every Passover celebration through the maror — the physical taste of oppression kept alive in covenant memory.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>vayomer melek Mitsrayim lameyaldot ha'ivriyot</strong>: 'The king of Egypt said to the Hebrew midwives.' The first named women in the Exodus narrative: Shiphrah and Puah — their names preserved while Pharaoh's is not. <em>Meyaldot</em> (midwives, from yalad H3205, bear/give birth): women who stand at the boundary between life and death, facilitating birth against the decree of death. The politics of empire confronts the politics of the womb.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>biyaldechem et-haivriyot ure'iten al-ha'avnayim</strong>: 'When you deliver the Hebrew women, look at the birthstool.' <em>Ha'avnayim</em> (H70, birthstool/two stones): possibly a dual form of even (stone), referring to the two stones or bricks on which a woman crouched for birth in the ancient Near East — attested in Egyptian birth scenes. The intimate setting of delivery is where Pharaoh demands that his death-decree be executed: infanticide disguised as midwifery.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>vatirena hameyaldot et-haElohim velo asu ka'asher diber aleihen melek Mitsrayim</strong>: 'The midwives feared God and did not do as the king of Egypt commanded.' <em>Yirat haElohim</em> (fear of God) vs. compliance with Pharaoh's command — the foundational ethical conflict of the Exodus. The midwives' <em>yirat Elohim</em> is the same phrase used for Abraham's faith (Gen 22:12: now I know you fear God) and the ethic of the stranger (Gen 20:11: there is no fear of God in this place). To fear God is to resist idolatrous human power.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>vayiqra melek Mitsrayim lameyaldot vayomer lahen madua asitem hadavar hazeh</strong>: 'The king of Egypt called the midwives and said: why have you done this thing?' The imperial interrogation of those who defied the decree. The midwives' answer — the Hebrew women are vigorous and give birth before we arrive (v.19) — is a deflection that preserves life. Civil disobedience that protects the innocent and deceives the oppressor is honored here: God blessed the midwives (v.20-21).</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>vatomernu hameyaldot el-Paroh ki lo kaNashim haMitsriyot haivriyot ki chayyot henah</strong>: 'The Hebrew women are not like the Egyptian women; they are vigorous (chayyot) and give birth before the midwife comes.' <em>Chayyot</em> (H2422, lively/vigorous, or possibly: like animals — they give birth easily): the midwives' response uses the vitality of the covenant people as their defense. The word <em>chayyot</em> is from <em>chayyah</em> (living/life) — the Hebrews' vitality is a mark of divine blessing.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>vayyeitav Elohim lameyaldot</strong>: 'God dealt well with the midwives.' The divine reward for those who fear God over imperial power: <em>vayyeitav</em> (was good to, from tov) — the goodness of God expressed in covenant blessing. The midwives received <em>batim</em> (households/families) — a covenantal blessing of progeny and stability, the very thing they had protected for others. Those who protect life receive life.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>vayhi ki-yareyu hameyaldot et-haElohim vayaas lahem batim</strong>: 'Because the midwives feared God, he gave them households.' The <em>bayit</em> (H1004, house/household) given to the midwives is simultaneously a domestic family unit and a dynastic legacy — the same word used for the house of David (2 Sam 7:11: YHWH will make you a house). Covenant faithfulness under persecution generates covenantal legacy. The midwives who preserved Israel's houses received houses of their own.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>kol-haben hayilod hayorah tashlichuhu</strong>: 'Every son who is born, throw him into the Nile.' Pharaoh's final decree — a public, universal death-sentence on Hebrew male children. The Nile, Egypt's source of life, is made the instrument of death. The anti-creation decree (Gen 1:28: be fruitful and multiply) is reversed: all that is born (yilod) is cast away. The decree anticipates and inverts the Passover: Egypt will lose its firstborn as it tried to kill Israel's sons. The measure used will be measured back (Matt 7:2).</p>"
},
"2": {
"1": "<p><strong>vayeikh ish mibet Levi vayiqach et-bat Levi</strong> (<em>wayyēleḵ ʾîš mibbet lēwî wayyiqqaḥ ʾet-bat lēwî</em>): 'A man from the house of Levi went and married a daughter of Levi.' The anonymity of Moses's parents — they are not named until Exod 6:20 (Amram and Jochebed) — focuses attention on the child rather than the lineage. Moses is from the tribe designated for priestly service (Levi), establishing his priestly identity before his prophetic commission. The double <em>Levi</em> (from Levi, daughter of Levi) underscores the covenantal continuity from the patriarchs.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>vatare oto ki-tov hu</strong> (<em>watteʾreʾ ʾōtô kî-ṭôb hûʾ</em>): 'She saw that he was good.' <em>Ki-tov</em> (that it was good): the precise phrase from the creation narrative (Gen 1:4, 10, 12, 18, 21, 25, 31 — God saw that it was good). Moses's mother recognizes in her infant the same goodness that YHWH recognized in creation. Stephen in Acts 7:20 uses <em>asteios</em> (beautiful/fair before God), and Hebrews 11:23 calls him <em>asteion</em> — the parents saw something God-given in the child. The creation-goodness language signals that Moses's birth is a new creative act.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>teva gome vatachmeraha bachemor uvazafet</strong> (<em>tēbat gōme wattaḥmĕrāh baḥēmār ûbazzāpet</em>): 'A basket of bulrushes/papyrus, she plastered it with bitumen and pitch.' <em>Teva</em> (H8392, ark/chest): the precise word used for Noah's ark (Gen 6:14-16) — only these two occurrences in the entire OT. Moses's basket is a miniature ark: like Noah, he is preserved in a <em>teva</em> through water while death surrounds. The pitch-and-bitumen coating echoes Noah's ark (Gen 6:14 — cover it with pitch inside and out). Both arks carry the seed of a new beginning through the waters of judgment.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>vateytsatazev achoto merachok lede'ah mah-ye'aseh lo</strong>: 'His sister stood at a distance to know what would be done for him.' Moses's unnamed sister (later Miriam, Exod 15:20) watches from a distance — a combination of care and prudential distance. The word <em>lede'ah</em> (to know, from yada) — she watches to know what will happen. Covenant protection often works through attentive human witness, the small acts of faithfulness that shelter the vulnerable.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>vateredu bat-Paroh lirchots al-hayeor</strong>: 'The daughter of Pharaoh came down to bathe at the Nile.' Pharaoh's own daughter, drawing from the Nile to which Hebrew sons were condemned, discovers and rescues the condemned child. The irony is structural: the instrument of death (the Nile, Pharaoh's decree) becomes the location of rescue, and the agent of rescue is from within the house of the oppressor. YHWH's providential sovereignty uses the empire's own household against its own decree.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>vatiftech vatirehu et-hayeled vehinei naar boche vatachemel alav</strong>: 'She opened it and saw the child — a boy crying; and she had compassion on him.' <em>Vatachemel alav</em> (she had compassion/pity on him): from <em>chamal</em> (H2550, have compassion/spare) — the spontaneous movement of the heart toward the suffering vulnerable. This compassion from within Pharaoh's own household is the surprise of grace: deliverance comes from unexpected places. The compassion of the divine is here mediated through a pagan princess.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>vatomer achoto el-bat Paroh haelich veqarati lach isha meineket min-haivriyot</strong>: 'His sister said to Pharaoh's daughter: Shall I go and call you a nurse from the Hebrew women?' The sister's intervention brings the child back to his own mother — he is nursed by his biological mother at Pharaoh's expense. Providence arranges that Moses receives his Hebrew identity at his mother's breast, even while living in Pharaoh's household. The covenant heritage is transmitted through the most intimate possible means.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>vateleich ha'alma vatiqra et-em hayaled</strong>: 'The young woman went and called the child's mother.' The chain of protection — mother, sister, princess — is the web of feminine courage that saves Moses. Multiple women act against the death-decree of a single man: the midwives (ch.1), Moses's mother, his sister, Pharaoh's daughter. The masculine power of empire is subverted by the feminine power of compassion. The Exodus begins with the courage of women.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>vatomer bat-Paroh helikhihu et-hayeled hazeh vehenikiehu li vaani etten et-secharch</strong>: 'Take this child and nurse him for me, and I will give you your wages.' Moses's mother is paid to nurse her own son. The irony of empire: Pharaoh's household funds the formation of its own deliverer. YHWH consistently uses the resources of the oppressor to equip those who will liberate the oppressed (cf. Israel's plundering of Egypt in Exod 12:35-36).</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>vatiqra shemo Mosheh vatomer ki min-hamayim meshitihu</strong> (<em>wattiqrāʾ šĕmô mōšeh wattōʾmer kî-min-hammayim mĕšîtîhû</em>): 'She called his name Moses, saying: for I drew him out of the water.' <em>Mosheh</em> (H4872) from <em>mashah</em> (H4871, draw out): the name-etymology given by Pharaoh's daughter — the Egyptian princess naming the Hebrew child after the act of rescue. A Hebrew passive form would mean one who is drawn out; an active form, one who draws out. Both work: Moses is drawn out of the Nile and will draw Israel out of Egypt. The name is a vocation compressed into a sound.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>vayehi bayamim hahem vayigdal Mosheh vayetze el-echav vayar besivolotam</strong>: 'In those days, when Moses had grown up, he went out to his brothers and looked at their burdens.' <em>Vayar besivolotam</em> (he saw their burdens): Moses's seeing echoes YHWH's seeing in 3:7 (ra'o raiti et-oni ammi). The prophet who will mediate YHWH's deliverance first personally sees what YHWH has seen: the suffering of the covenant people. Stephen in Acts 7:23-24 identifies this as Moses's deliberate identification with his people, parallel to Christ's incarnational identification with human suffering (Heb 2:17-18).</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>vayifen ko vako vayar ki ein ish vayak et-haMitsri</strong>: 'He looked this way and that, and seeing no one, he struck the Egyptian.' The furtive glance before action — the consciousness of risk even in righteous response to injustice. Moses acts to defend the oppressed but through human agency that will need to be transformed. His zeal is real but his method (secret violence) is insufficient for the scale of liberation required. The Exodus will not be achieved by a single man's sword but by YHWH's mighty hand.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>vayetze bayom hasheni vehinei shnei anashim ivrim nitsim</strong>: 'On the second day he went out and saw two Hebrew men quarreling.' The internal conflict within the oppressed community — the violence of empire internalized among its victims. The divided Hebrew community that rejects its own deliverer anticipates the pattern of Israel's repeated rejection of Moses in the wilderness (Exod 16-17; Num 14) and ultimately of the prophet like Moses (Acts 7:35-39).</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>mi samcha le'ish sar veshofet aleinu</strong> (<em>mî śāmĕkā lĕʾîš śar wĕšōpēṭ ʿālênû</em>): 'Who made you a prince and a judge over us?' The Hebrew slave's challenge to Moses's authority is quoted by Stephen in Acts 7:35 as typological of Israel's rejection of Christ: this Moses, whom they rejected saying who made you a ruler and judge? — this man God sent as both ruler and redeemer. The rejection of Moses the deliverer prefigures the rejection of the deliverer Moses pointed to.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>vayishma Paroh et-hadavar hazeh vayevaqesh lahrog et-Mosheh vayivarch Mosheh mipnei Paroh</strong>: 'Pharaoh heard this thing and sought to kill Moses, and Moses fled from Pharaoh's face.' The exile of Moses to Midian is both flight from imperial violence and the necessary preparation for the burning-bush commission. The wilderness period (forty years, Acts 7:30) shapes the deliverer before deployment. Jesus's forty days in the wilderness (Matt 4:1-11) compresses the Mosaic forty-year preparation into forty days of tested faithfulness.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>ulekhohen Midyan sheva banot</strong>: 'The priest of Midian had seven daughters.' Moses encounters the daughters of Jethro (Reuel) at the well — the third great well-meeting in Genesis-Exodus (Isaac-Rebekah, Gen 24; Jacob-Rachel, Gen 29; now Moses-Zipporah). Wells are covenant meeting places in the OT: the place where the wandering stranger finds the one who will become the link to his future. Moses is now a stranger without a people — the well scene marks his transition from Egyptian prince to Midianite sojourner.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>vayaqom Mosheh vayoshien vayashq et-tsonam</strong>: 'Moses stood up and helped them and watered their flock.' Moses's defense of the women against the hostile shepherds reveals his character: he uses his strength on behalf of the vulnerable. The shepherd who defends his flock — against hostile shepherds, against beasts — is the role Moses will now learn by tending Jethro's flock and that he will exercise for Israel for forty years in the wilderness. The Good Shepherd's character is forged in Midian.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>madu'a mihartem bo hayom</strong>: 'Why have you come home so early today?' Jethro's question to his daughters reveals the normal situation: the well is contested, the women are routinely driven away. Moses's intervention was exceptional — not merely polite but decisive. The same word <em>madua</em> (why) opens the commission narrative in 3:3 (madua lo-yivar hasneh, why is the bush not burning up) — the question that opens perception to the unexpected.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>ish Mitsri hitstsileinu miyad haro'im</strong>: 'An Egyptian man delivered us from the hand of the shepherds.' The daughters identify Moses as Egyptian — he looks Egyptian, speaks Egyptian, acts with Egyptian authority. Moses is a man without a clear identity: Hebrew by birth, Egyptian by formation, stranger in Midian. The deliverer is always the outsider within — Joseph in Egypt, Daniel in Babylon, Christ in Judea (John 1:11: he came to his own, and his own people did not receive him).</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>ve'ayeh lamdua zeh azavtem et-ha'ish</strong>: 'Where is he? Why did you leave the man?' Jethro's characteristic hospitality — the expectation that a stranger who acts with such character should be invited to share the table. <em>Kireu lo ve'yochal lachem</em> (call him to eat bread): table fellowship as covenant-initiation. The shared meal is always a covenant act in the OT (cf. Gen 31:54; Exod 18:12). Moses enters Jethro's household through bread.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>vayoel Mosheh lashevet et-ha'ish vayiten et-Tziporah bito leMosheh</strong>: 'Moses agreed to stay with the man, and he gave Moses his daughter Zipporah.' <em>Vayoel</em> (H2974, agreed/consented): the verb suggests a deliberate choice — Moses makes Midian his home. The marriage to Zipporah grounds Moses in a new family before he returns to his first family. The name <em>Tziporah</em> (H6855) means bird — perhaps signaling freedom or swift movement. Moses's Midianite period is not wasted exile but essential formation.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>vateled ben vayiqra et-shemo Gershom ki amar ger hayiti be'eretz nochriya</strong>: 'She bore a son, and he called his name Gershom, saying: I have been a stranger in a foreign land.' <em>Gershom</em> (H1648): word-play on <em>ger</em> (H1616, stranger/sojourner) + <em>sham</em> (there) — stranger-there. Moses names his son after his own identity crisis: the deliverer of Israel is himself a displaced person, a stranger. The <em>ger</em> identity will shape Israel's ethics: you shall not oppress a stranger, for you know the soul of the stranger, having been strangers in Egypt (Exod 23:9).</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>vayehi vayamim harabim hahem vayamot melek Mitsrayim vayane'anchu bnei Yisrael min-ha'avoda vayizaqu</strong>: 'During those many days the king of Egypt died, and the Israelites groaned because of their slavery and cried out.' <em>Na'aqah</em> (H5009, groan/cry out): the deep involuntary cry of those crushed beyond endurance. <em>Tzaaq</em> (H6818, cry out): the urgent legal cry to a superior for relief. Both words together emphasize the totality of Israel's anguish — involuntary suffering-cry and deliberate appeal. The Exodus begins with a groan that ascends to heaven.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>vayishma Elohim et-na'aqatam vayizkor Elohim et-berito et-Avraham et-Yitzchak ve'et-Yaakov</strong> (<em>wayyišmaʿ ʾĕlōhîm ʾet-naʾăqātām wayyizĕkor ʾĕlōhîm ʾet-bĕrîtô ʾet-ʾabrāhām ʾet-yiṣḥāq wĕʾet-yaʿăqōb</em>): 'God heard their groaning and God remembered his covenant with Abraham, with Isaac, and with Jacob.' The four verbs of divine response in vv.24-25: heard (<em>shama</em>), remembered (<em>zakar</em>), saw (<em>ra'ah</em>), knew/took note (<em>yada</em>). <em>Zakar</em> (H2142, remember) is not mere mental recall but performative memory — God remembering the covenant is God activating it. The covenant made with three patriarchs is invoked with all three names: no generation of covenant is excluded.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>vayar Elohim et-bnei Yisrael vayeda Elohim</strong> (<em>wayyarʾ ʾĕlōhîm ʾet-bĕnê yiśrāʾēl wayyēdaʿ ʾĕlōhîm</em>): 'God saw the children of Israel and God knew.' The verse ends simply: <em>vayeda Elohim</em> — and God knew. <em>Yada</em> (H3045, know/take note of) as covenantal recognition: YHWH does not merely observe Israel's condition but enters into it — knowing as intimate concern and committed response. The brevity of the verse amplifies its weight: the entire Exodus is set in motion by these four words. God's knowing is God's acting.</p>"
},
"3": {
"1": "<p><strong>uMosheh hayah ro'eh et-tson Yitro chotno kohen Midyan</strong> (<em>ûmōšeh hāyāh rōʿeh ʾet-ṣōʾn yitrô ḥōtnô kōhēn midyān</em>): 'Moses was shepherding the flock of Jethro his father-in-law, the priest of Midian.' The great deliverer of Israel is introduced as a shepherd — the paradigmatic leadership role in the biblical imagination. Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Joseph, David, and Christ (John 10:11) are all shepherds. <em>Kohen Midyan</em> (priest of Midian) — Jethro as a Gentile priest suggests that knowledge of the divine was not limited to Israel, though the definitive self-disclosure comes through Moses and at Sinai.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>vayera malach YHWH elav belabat-esh mitoch hasneh</strong> (<em>wayyērāʾ malʾaḵ Yhwh ʾēlāw bĕlabbat-ʾēš mittôḵ hassĕneh</em>): 'The angel of the LORD appeared to him in a flame of fire from within the thornbush.' <em>Malach YHWH</em> (H4397 + H3068, messenger/angel of the LORD): the divine messenger who is functionally identified with YHWH himself throughout the OT (as here — v.4: YHWH called to him; v.6: I am the God of your father). The <em>sneh</em> (H5572, thornbush): a common, scrubby desert plant — the divine glory dwelling in the ordinary, the humble location of the holiest revelation. The fire that does not consume the bush is the presence that dwells in the lowly without destroying it.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>vayomer Mosheh asura na ve'er'eh et-hama're haGadol hazeh madua lo-yivar hasneh</strong>: 'Moses said: Let me turn aside and see this great sight — why is the bush not burned?' <em>Asura na</em> (let me turn aside): Moses's voluntary turning — the pivot that leads to encounter. The question <em>madua</em> (why?) marks Moses as one whose curiosity opens him to revelation. Heraclitus said that the unexamined life is not worth living; the biblical corollary is that the uncurious eye misses divine disclosure. Moses's willingness to leave his path and investigate is what brings him into YHWH's presence.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>vayar YHWH ki sar lir'ot vayiqra elav Elohim mitoch hasneh vayomer Mosheh Mosheh vayomer hineni</strong>: 'When YHWH saw that he turned aside to see, God called to him out of the bush: Moses! Moses! And he said: Here I am.' The doubled name <em>Mosheh Mosheh</em> is the address of urgency and intimacy — only used for figures in decisive covenant-encounter (Abraham in Gen 22:11; Jacob in Gen 46:2; Samuel in 1 Sam 3:10). <em>Hineni</em> (H2009, here I am): the covenantal response of complete availability — the same response that Abraham (Gen 22:1) and Isaiah (Isa 6:8) gave at their defining moments of commission.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>al-tiqrav halom shal-ne'alecha me'al raglecha ki hamakom asher ata omed alav admat-qodesh hu</strong>: 'Do not come near here; remove your sandals from your feet, for the place on which you are standing is holy ground.' <em>Admat qodesh</em> (H127 + H6944, holy ground/soil): the ground becomes holy by the divine presence — holiness is not a property of places but of YHWH's dwelling. Joshua receives the same command before Jericho (Josh 5:15: remove your sandals from your feet, for the place where you are standing is holy). The bare foot on holy ground signals that the human approaches naked — without any human covering or pretension.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>anochi Elohei avicha Elohei Avraham Elohei Yitzchak ve'Elohei Yaakov</strong> (<em>ʾānōkî ʾĕlōhê ʾābîkā ʾĕlōhê ʾabrāhām ʾĕlōhê yiṣḥāq wĕʾĕlōhê yaʿăqōb</em>): 'I am the God of your father, the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob.' The four-fold divine identification grounds the Sinai revelation in the patriarchal covenant — the God now speaking is not a new deity but the same covenant God of three generations. Jesus cites this verse in the resurrection debate (Mark 12:26-27): God said I am (not I was) the God of Abraham — YHWH identifies himself as God of those who are alive, not dead. The present tense of divine self-identification reveals the resurrection.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>ra'o raiti et-oni ammi asher beMitsrayim</strong> (<em>rāʾōh rāʾîtî ʾet-ʿŏnî ʿammî ʾăšer bĕmiṣrāyim</em>): 'I have surely seen the affliction of my people who are in Egypt.' <em>Ra'o raiti</em>: infinitive absolute + perfect — the most emphatic Hebrew construction (truly seen, seen with seeing). The doubled seeing is YHWH's emphasis that his attention has not been absent or inattentive. <em>Oni</em> (H6040, affliction/poverty/misery): the same root as the oppression of v.1:11-12 (<em>anah</em>). <em>Ammi</em> (my people): YHWH claims Israel as his own — not merely a people he created but a people he owns in covenant. The possessive <em>ammi</em> is the ground of the Exodus.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>vaered lehatsilo miyad Mitsrayim ulehaaloto min-ha'aretz hahi el-eretz tova verechava el-eretz zavat chalav udevash</strong>: 'I have come down to deliver him from the hand of Egypt and to bring him up out of that land to a good and broad land, a land flowing with milk and honey.' The two movements of divine rescue: <em>yered</em> (come down, descend) to deliver, then <em>alah</em> (bring up, ascend) to the promised land. YHWH's descending is the incarnational pattern of divine rescue. <em>Eretz zavat chalav udevash</em> (land flowing with milk and honey): the standard covenantal description of Canaan (used 20+ times); milk and honey represent pastoral abundance (livestock) and agricultural sweetness.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>gam ra'iti et-halacatz asher Mitsrayim lochatzim otam</strong>: 'I have also seen the oppression with which the Egyptians oppress them.' <em>Lachatz</em> (H3906, oppression/pressure) — the crushing pressure of empire on the covenant people. The doubled seeing (v.7 and v.9) intensifies the theological claim: YHWH has seen both the suffering of his people and the active oppression of their oppressors. The Exodus is both a rescue and a judgment — YHWH acting as both savior and judge simultaneously.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>ve'atah lecha ve'eshlachacha el-Paroh vehotse et-ami bnei Yisrael miMitsrayim</strong>: 'And now go, and I will send you to Pharaoh that you may bring my people, the children of Israel, out of Egypt.' The commission: YHWH's seeing becomes YHWH's sending. The pattern of prophetic commission throughout the OT (Isaiah in 6:8-9; Jeremiah in 1:7-8; Ezekiel in 2:3-4): the one who has seen the divine glory is sent to the people. The divine imperative (go) is backed by the divine resource (I will send you — the verb <em>shalach</em> guarantees the sender's authority stands behind the sent one).</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>mi anochi ki elech el-Paroh</strong>: 'Who am I that I should go to Pharaoh?' Moses's first objection. <em>Mi anochi</em> (who am I?): the rhetorical question of inadequacy — the same that Gideon asks (Judg 6:15), Saul asks (1 Sam 9:21), and David asks (2 Sam 7:18). The question is not false modesty but a real reckoning with human limitation before divine commission. The answer is not a reassurance of Moses's adequacy but a promise of divine presence: <em>ki ehyeh imach</em> (for I will be with you) — the commission rests on YHWH's presence, not Moses's competence.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>vayomer ki ehyeh imach</strong> (<em>wayyōʾmer kî-ʾehyeh ʿimmāḵ</em>): 'He said: for I will be with you.' <em>Ki ehyeh imach</em> — the promise of divine presence that answers every human inadequacy. <em>Ehyeh</em> (H1961, I will be): the first-person imperfect of <em>hayah</em> (to be) — the same root that becomes the divine name in v.14. YHWH's self-revelation as I AM is grounded in his promise of I-will-be-with-you: the divine name announces the covenantal presence. The sign given is counter-intuitive: this is the sign — after you bring the people out you will worship on this mountain. The proof of the commission comes at its completion, not before.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>veyamru li mah shmo mah omar aleihem</strong>: 'They will say to me: What is his name? What shall I say to them?' Moses's second objection — anticipating the question of authority. In the ancient world, knowing a divine name was knowing the basis for appeal. The Israelites ask not merely for information but for a ground of trust: which god has sent you, and can we count on him? The answer Moses receives exceeds all expectation — not a name that places YHWH among other gods but a name that transcends the category.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>YHWH Elohei avoteichem Elohei Avraham Elohei Yitzchak ve'Elohei Yaakov shlachani aleiichem zeh shmi le'olam vezeh zikri ledor dor</strong> (<em>Yhwh ʾĕlōhê ʾăbōtêkem ʾĕlōhê ʾabrāhām ʾĕlōhê yiṣḥāq wĕʾĕlōhê yaʿăqōb šĕlāḥanî ʾălêkem zeh šĕmî lĕʿōlām wĕzeh zikĕrî lĕdōr dōr</em>): 'YHWH, God of your fathers, God of Abraham, God of Isaac, and God of Jacob, has sent me to you. This is my name forever, and this is my memorial for all generations.' The Tetragrammaton established as the permanent covenant name: <em>le'olam</em> (forever) and <em>ledor dor</em> (generation to generation). The name revealed in v.14 (<em>ehyeh asher ehyeh</em>) is now given its public form as <em>YHWH</em> — the third-person form of the same <em>hayah</em> root (He who IS/causes to be). Every generation of the covenant community calls on the same name.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>leich ve'asafta et-ziknei Yisrael</strong>: 'Go and gather the elders of Israel.' The community-structure through which the divine word is mediated: the elders (<em>zeqenim</em>, H2205) are the representative leadership of the tribal covenant community. Before Moses addresses Pharaoh, he must address Israel's own leaders. The divine commission is not a solo heroic act but a communal call: the deliverer must first secure the covenant community's participation in their own liberation.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>va'omar alachem me'oni Mitsrayim</strong>: 'I will bring you up from the affliction of Egypt.' The divine announcement before the event: YHWH promises the Exodus before it happens, establishing faith as the anticipation of fulfilled promise. The pattern of promise-then-fulfillment is the structure of all biblical covenant: what God says he will do becomes the ground of present trust even before the evidence is visible.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>veshamu leqolecha</strong>: 'They will listen to your voice.' YHWH's assurance that the elders will hear — but the assurance is immediately followed by the warning that Pharaoh will not (v.19: I know that the king of Egypt will not let you go). The contrast structures the Exodus: Israel will hear; Pharaoh will not. The capacity to hear is a covenant gift — those within the covenant community have ears to hear what Pharaoh's hardened heart cannot receive.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>va'ani yodea ki lo-yiten etchem melek Mitsrayim lahaloch</strong>: 'I know that the king of Egypt will not let you go unless compelled by a mighty hand.' YHWH's foreknowledge of Pharaoh's refusal is not the cause of it — Pharaoh will harden his own heart first (Exod 7:13-14) before YHWH confirms the hardening. The mighty hand (<em>yad chazaqah</em>) that overcomes the refusal is the same mighty hand by which YHWH brought Israel out of Egypt — the Exodus formula for divine power.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>veshalach et-yadi vehiketi et-Mitsrayim bechol nifle'otai</strong>: 'I will stretch out my hand and strike Egypt with all my wonders.' <em>Nifle'otai</em> (H6381, my wonders/marvelous acts): the plagues are YHWH's wonders — acts that exceed natural causation and display divine power. <em>Nifla'ot</em> is cognate with <em>pele</em> (wonder, H6382) — used for YHWH's incomprehensible acts (Ps 77:14; 78:11-12; 105:5) and for the name of the angel of the LORD (Judg 13:18). The plagues are not arbitrary punishment but the pedagogical display of YHWH's incomparable power.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>venatati et-chen ha'am hazeh be'einei Mitsrayim</strong>: 'I will give this people favor in the sight of the Egyptians.' <em>Chen</em> (H2580, favor/grace): YHWH sovereignly disposing the Egyptians to give generously to their departing slaves. The plundering of Egypt (v.22) is not theft but the providential reversal of the oppression — the labor never compensated is now paid in kind. Paul cites a similar providential generosity in 2 Cor 8:21: we aim at what is honorable.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>ve'nitzaltem et-Mitsrayim</strong> (<em>wĕniṣṣaltem ʾet-miṣrāyim</em>): 'You shall plunder Egypt.' <em>Nitzal</em> (H5337, plunder/strip) — the same root used for rescue/deliverance elsewhere (YHWH nitzal Israel from enemies). The plunder of Egypt is the material counterpart to the spiritual deliverance: the covenant people leave with both freedom and provision, equipped for the wilderness ahead. The pattern of deliverance that includes material provision recurs in Christ's commission to the disciples: he sends them out with provision (Luke 10:7 — the laborer deserves his wages).</p>"
}
}

